What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset comprises 183,412 rides with 16 features, primarily numeric in nature. However, some variables, such as 'start_time' and 'end_time', have incorrect data types and should be converted to datetime. Additionally, the columns 'start_station_id', 'start_station_name', 'end_station_id', 'end_station_name', 'member_birth_year', and 'member_gender' contain missing values.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest in this dataset is duration_sec, start_time, and user_type column.and I'm interested in analyzing the time of day and the day of the week when the most trips are taken.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

# a function as requested to avoid reptive code
def create_countplot(data, x_var, hue_var=None, order=None, title=None, xlabel=None, rotation=0):
    plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
    ax = sns.countplot(data=data, x=x_var, hue=hue_var, order=order, color=sns.color_palette()[0])
    total = len(data)
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.3f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height() / total)
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2
        y = p.get_height() + .05
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), ha='center')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.xticks(rotation=rotation)
    plt.show()

# Sample usage of the function
# Plot for ride frequency per month
create_countplot(bike, 'end_month', title='Ride Frequency per Month', order=bike.end_month.value_counts().index)

# Plot for ride frequency per gender
create_countplot(bike, 'member_gender', title='Ride Frequency per Gender', order=bike.member_gender.value_counts().index)

# Plot for ride frequency per user type
create_countplot(bike, 'user_type', title='Ride Frequency per User Type', order=bike.user_type.value_counts().index)

Conclusions¶

Less than 10% of the trips involved bike sharing for all trips. The majority of trips were taken by males, accounting for over 70% of the total. Customers tend to have longer trip durations compared to subscribers. Female riders generally spend more time on trips than male riders. Trip durations are longer on weekends compared to weekdays. Only subscribers are permitted to share bikes during trips. The customer type does not significantly influence the number of trips taken on each weekday. Customers tend to travel for longer durations regardless of the day of the week. The dataset covers trips taken in February and March 2019.
